    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "88VwFdWBCFkC"
      },
      "source": [
        "#### 3.2.9 Looping vs Vectorization\n",
        "\n",
        "As mentioned in the beginning, NumPy uses machine code with their ndarray objects which is what leads to the performance improvements. Let's demonstrate this by constructing a simple sine wave."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "mX9awPKn-ZlU",
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "outputId": "a4052c23-7ef0-4eb2-b220-5336649d2dd2"
      },
      "source": [
        "fs = 500 #sampling rate in Hz\n",
        "d_t = 1 / fs #time steps in seconds\n",
        "n_step = 1000 #number of steps (there will be n_step+1 data points)\n",
        "\n",
        "amp = 1 #amplitude of sine wave\n",
        "f = 2 #frequency of sine wave\n",
        "\n",
        "time = np.linspace(0,             #start time\n",
        "                   n_step * d_t,    #end time\n",
        "                   num=n_step + 1)  #number of data points, one more than the steps to include an endpoint\n",
        "time.shape"
      ],
      "execution_count": 188,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "execute_result",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "(1001,)"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 188
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "CIKO7e0e0QvP"
      },
      "source": [
        "First we make a function to loop through each element and calculate the amplitude."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "wqVZJKtwTB8l"
      },
      "source": [
        "def sine_wave_with_loop(time, amp, f, phase=0):\n",
        "  length = time.shape[0]\n",
        "  wave = np.zeros(length)\n",
        "\n",
        "  for i in range(length-1):\n",
        "    wave[i] = np.sin(2 * np.pi * f * time[i] + phase * np.pi / 180)*amp\n",
        "  return wave"
      ],
      "execution_count": 189,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8nkt7EDc0c3H"
      },
      "source": [
        "Now let's time how quickly that executes for our time array of 1,001 data points."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "CMwHGKrITpN4",
        "outputId": "f7203275-ec8d-478c-ca1f-42df85cf5d06"
      },
      "source": [
        "%timeit sine_wave_with_loop(time, amp, f)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 190,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "2.03 ms ± 323 µs per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 1000 loops each)\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "g4s7-D_90nNH"
      },
      "source": [
        "Now let's do the same using NumPy's sine function and vectorization."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "89xWQJpzAdal"
      },
      "source": [
        "def sine_wave_with_numpy(time, amp, f, phase=0):\n",
        "  \"\"\"Takes in a time array and sine wave parameters, returns an array of the sine wave amplitude.\"\"\"\n",
        "  return np.sin(2 * np.pi * f * time + phase * np.pi / 180) * amp"
      ],
      "execution_count": 191,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6rNJady-0sJp"
      },
      "source": [
        "Notice my docstrings!"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "AsVkSRvtV3HI",
        "outputId": "e8b57876-a607-442c-d2ca-7bcf47bae0e3"
      },
      "source": [
        "help(sine_wave_with_numpy)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 192,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Help on function sine_wave_with_numpy in module __main__:\n",
            "\n",
            "sine_wave_with_numpy(time, amp, f, phase=0)\n",
            "    Takes in a time array and sine wave parameters, returns an array of the sine wave amplitude.\n",
            "\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "Q5S5fTrw--Z3",
        "outputId": "a9322de3-ded2-41ee-a001-c5a59c44e116"
      },
      "source": [
        "%timeit sine_wave_with_numpy(time, amp, f)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 193,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "23 µs ± 693 ns per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 10000 loops each)\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "jtS0wmIyppOW"
      },
      "source": [
        "Using vectorization is about **100x faster!** And this increases the longer the loops are."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KQIddnfwp7t5"
      },
      "source": [
        "#### 3.2.10 Why Vectorization Works So Much Faster\n",
        "The above example highlights that NumPy is much faster, but why? Because it is using compiled machine code under the hood for it's operations.\n",
        "\n",
        "Python has the [Numba](http://numba.pydata.org/) package which can be used to do this compilation which we will do to highlight just why NumPy is faster (and recommended!)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cX8PSvkRoJR3"
      },
      "source": [
        "from numba import njit\n",
        "\n",
        "numba_sine_wave_with_loop = njit(sine_wave_with_loop)\n",
        "numba_sine_wave_with_numpy = njit(sine_wave_with_numpy)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 194,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "T_ckZKtlo1IJ",
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "outputId": "115212a1-76fa-45fa-ffeb-b9976fce8092"
      },
      "source": [
        "%timeit numba_sine_wave_with_loop(time, amp, f)\n",
        "%timeit numba_sine_wave_with_numpy(time, amp, f)"
      ],
      "execution_count": 195,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "20.1 µs ± 2.82 µs per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 100000 loops each)\n",
            "30.7 µs ± 973 ns per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 10000 loops each)\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
